the Medieval Mediterranean World -- tBenefaction (Ni ma), Gratitude (Shukr), and the Politics of Giving and Receiving in Letters from the Cairo Geniza -- tAn Indigent Scholar’s Plea for Charity: A Geniza Letter0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book deals with various manifestations of charity or giving in the contexts of the Christian, Jewish, and Muslim societies in Late Antiquity and Early Middle Ages. Monotheistic charity and giving display many common features. These underlying similarities reflect a commonly shared view about God and his relations to mankind and what humans owe to God and expect from him. Nevertheless, the fact that the emphasis is placed on similarities does not mean that the uniqueness of the concepts of charity and giving in the three monotheistic religions is denied. The contributors of the book deal with such heterogeneous topics like the language of social justice in early Christian homilies as well as charity and pious endowments in medieval Syria, Egypt and al-Andalus during the 11th-15th centuries. This wide range of approaches distinguish the book from other works on charity and giving in monotheistic religions.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aCharity. 0aGenerosityxReligious aspects. 0aGenerosity. 0aMonotheism. 4aReligion. 4aSchenken. 4aWohltätigkeit. 7aRELIGION / Comparative Religion.2bisacsh  aCharity, Christian.  aCharity, Jewish.  aCharity, Muslim.  aCharity, medieval and ancient.  aGiving.1 aCaner, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarballeira Debasa, Ana María, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Mark R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1